<subSubSection id="97C03CFDFF89FF9AFF7EFE6BFA6BFC14" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" type="description">
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF89FF9AFF7EFE6BFD0AFCA0" blockId="8.[136,1452,446,1841]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF7EFE6BFEE5FE38" bold="true" box="[136,274,446,472]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Description</emphasis>
(after 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFE95FE6BFDECFE38" author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[355,539,446,472]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" refId="ref33002" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2008) Water starworts of Europe. BSBI Handbook No. 11. Botanical Society of the British Isles, London, UK. 180 pp." type="book" year="2008">Lansdown 2008</bibRefCitation>
):—Stem, leaf and axillary scales present. Leaf bases connate. Lingulate leaves 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFF7EFE37FF05FE1D" box="[136,242,482,509]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="0.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="10.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="4.0">4–16 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFEB2FE37FE3DFE1D" box="[324,458,482,509]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="17.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="0.9" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="0.1">0.1–1.7 mm</quantity>
wide, narrowly linear, more or less parallel-sided, apex expanded, with a long, fine, broad or narrow notch; expanded submerged or floating leaves narrowly elliptic to oblong 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFBCFFDD3FB38FDC1" box="[1081,1231,518,545]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.8" metricValueMax="17.8" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="9.8" valueMax="17.8" valueMin="1.8">1.8–17.8 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFAD3FDD3FA5BFDC1" box="[1317,1452,518,545]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="3.6" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="2.2" valueMax="3.6" valueMin="0.8">0.8–3.6 mm</quantity>
wide, 3(–5)-veined, petiole 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFE49FDFFFDA3FDA5" box="[447,596,554,581]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1499999999999995" metricValueMax="10.2" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="5.1499999999999995" valueMax="10.2" valueMin="0.1">0.1–10.2 mm</quantity>
long; apical leaves form a floating rosette; leaves of terrestrial plants linearelliptic to elliptic, 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFEA0FD9BFE2AFD89" box="[342,477,590,617]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.95" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="3.95" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="2.4">2.4–5.5 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFDC5FD9BFD4DFD89" box="[563,698,590,617]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.8 mm</quantity>
wide, 1(–3)-veined. Flowers generally solitary, a 
<specimenCount id="C9DCA4FFFF89FF9AFB1EFD9AFB0AFD89" box="[1256,1277,591,617]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="C9DCA4FFFF89FF9AFAC5FD9AFABFFD89" box="[1331,1352,591,617]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
in a pair of axils occasionally more than one in an axil. Bracts translucent, whitish, falcate, caducous, 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFB6FFDA7FAD7FD6D" box="[1177,1312,626,653]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="0.2">0.2–1.8 mm</quantity>
long. Styles persistent, tightly reflexed and appressed to sides of fruit from the initial stages of development, so that the styles pass either side of the stem to touch the anther in the opposed axil, ≤ 4.1(–4.3) mm long. Filament erect, ≤ 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFAA2FD6FFA5BFD35" box="[1364,1452,698,725]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
long; anthers 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFED7FD0BFE5FFD19" box="[289,424,734,761]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="0.3" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.5 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFE09FD0BFD71FD19" box="[511,646,734,761]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="0.35" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.1">0.1–0.6 mm</quantity>
wide, quadrilocular; pollen colourless, translucent. Fruits not strumose, subsessile or with pedicel ≤ 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFE34FCD7FDE7FCFD" box="[450,528,770,797]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
long, more or less as wide as or wider than high, blackish or maroon when mature, 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFF7EFCF3FEF8FCA1" box="[136,271,806,833]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.6" valueMin="0.7">0.7–1.6 mm</quantity>
long × 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFE93FCF3FE1BFCA1" box="[357,492,806,833]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="mm" value="1.25" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="0.7">0.7–1.8 mm</quantity>
wide, narrowly winged.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF89FF9AFF4BFC9FFE02FC68" blockId="8.[136,1452,446,1841]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF4BFC9FFEAEFC84" bold="true" box="[189,345,842,868]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Illustrations:</emphasis>
—Figures in 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFE1DFC9FFD47FC84" author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[491,688,842,868]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" refId="ref33002" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2008) Water starworts of Europe. BSBI Handbook No. 11. Botanical Society of the British Isles, London, UK. 180 pp." type="book" year="2008">Lansdown (2008)</bibRefCitation>
pages 132–135; 
<figureCitation id="47E173F3FF89FF9AFC9AFC9FFC17FC85" box="[876,992,842,869]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="19.[136,229,1126,1148]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,245,1101]" captionTargetId="figure-47@19.[151,1436,245,1101]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 11 C. muelleri Tiritiri Matangi, North Island, New Zealand, 2011 © R.V. Lansdown" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577555" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577555/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Figures 11</figureCitation>
(a–b), 11A(a–c) in 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFB45FC9EFAA4FC85" author="Mason, R." box="[1203,1363,842,869]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" pagination="295 - 327" refId="ref33979" refString="Mason, R. (1959) Callitriche in New Zealand and Australia. Australian Journal of Botany 7: 295 - 327. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / BT 9590295" type="journal article" year="1959">Mason (1959)</bibRefCitation>
; figures 1J–L in 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFF15FCBBFE64FC68" author="Orchard, A. E." box="[227,403,878,904]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" pagination="191 - 194" refId="ref34641" refString="Orchard, A. E. (1980) Callitriche (Callitrichaceae) in South Australia. Journal of the Adelaide Botanic Garden 2: 191 - 194." type="journal article" year="1980">Orchard (1980)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<figureCitation id="47E173F3FF89FF9AFE68FCBBFE07FC68" box="[414,496,878,904]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,225,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-31@4.[151,1436,190,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Fruits of Callitriche in Oceania and Australasia: a—C. antarctica, b—C. aucklandica, c—C. brachycarpa, d—C. brutia, e—C. capricorni, f—C. chathamensis, g—C. cyclocarpa i face on and ii end on, h—C. cycloptera, i—C. deflexa, j—C. fuliginea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577540/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF89FF9AFF4BFC47FA6BFC14" blockId="8.[136,1452,446,1841]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF4BFC47FEA1FC4C" bold="true" box="[189,342,914,940]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Recognition:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFE84FC46FE2CFC4C" authorityName="Petagna" authorityYear="1787" box="[370,475,914,941]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brutia">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFE84FC46FE2CFC4C" box="[370,475,914,941]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">C. brutia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFC7DFC47FB96FC4C" box="[907,1121,914,940]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFC7DFC47FBF3FC4C" box="[907,1028,914,940]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Callitriche</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by the reflexed style which initially crosses the stem to contact an anther in the opposite leaf axil and of which the remains are typically appressed to the commissural groove of mature fruit (
<figureCitation id="47E173F3FF89FF9AFD9AFC0FFD4AFC15" box="[620,701,986,1013]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1943,1965]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,225,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-31@4.[151,1436,190,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Fruits of Callitriche in Oceania and Australasia: a—C. antarctica, b—C. aucklandica, c—C. brachycarpa, d—C. brutia, e—C. capricorni, f—C. chathamensis, g—C. cyclocarpa i face on and ii end on, h—C. cycloptera, i—C. deflexa, j—C. fuliginea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577540" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577540/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
). No other 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFCCBFC0FFBF9FC14" box="[829,1038,986,1012]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFCCBFC0FFC41FC14" box="[829,950,986,1012]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Callitriche</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in the region has colourless pollen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="97C03CFDFF89FF9AFF4BFC2BFD54F8D1" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF89FF9AFF4BFC2BFA80FB10" blockId="8.[136,1452,446,1841]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF4BFC2BFEAEFBF8" bold="true" box="[189,345,1022,1048]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Distribution:</emphasis>
—Non-native to the region, where it occurs throughout Victoria and southern New South Wales (
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFF79FBF7FEA0FBDC" author="Webb, C. J. &amp; Sykes, W. R. &amp; Garnock-Jones, P. J." box="[143,343,1058,1085]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" refId="ref37555" refString="Webb, C. J., Sykes, W. R. &amp; Garnock-Jones, P. J. (1988) Flora of New Zealand. Vol. IV. Naturalised Pteridophytes, Gymnosperms, Dicotyledons. Botany Division D. S. I. R., Christchurch, New Zealand." type="book" year="1988">
Webb 
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF2CFBF6FEFAFBDC" box="[218,269,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">et al</emphasis>
. 1988
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFE92FBF6FE05FBDC" author="Jeanes, J. A." box="[356,498,1058,1085]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" refId="ref32394" refString="Jeanes, J. A. (1999) Callitrichaceae. In Walsh, N. G. &amp; Entwisle, T. J. (Eds.) Flora of Victoria. Vol 1. Dicotyledons, Cornaceae to Asteraceae. Inkata Press, Melbourne, Australia." type="book" year="1999">Jeanes 1999</bibRefCitation>
), with a few records from South Australia and a cluster of records south of Perth in Western Australia, as well as from between Matakohe and Ruawai near the Karipara Harbour on North Island and Lake Elterwater on South Island in 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFDD6FBBEFD4FFB64" box="[544,696,1130,1157]" name="New Zealand" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="47E173F3FF89FF9AFD3FFBBFFCE7FB64" box="[713,784,1130,1156]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1655,1677]" captionTargetBox="[281,1310,984,1621]" captionTargetId="figure-34@7.[273,1314,974,1631]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. The distribution of specimens of C. brutia in Oceania and Australasia based on records held by AVH." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6577546" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6577546/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Outside Oceania, 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFC07FBBEFBAFFB64" authorityName="Petagna" authorityYear="1787" box="[1009,1112,1130,1157]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brutia">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFC07FBBEFBAFFB64" box="[1009,1112,1130,1157]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">C. brutia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native throughout much of Europe, from 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFED4FB5BFE83FB48" box="[290,372,1166,1192]" name="Iceland" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Iceland</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFE27FB5AFD9FFB48" box="[465,616,1166,1193]" name="Faroe Islands" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Faroe Islands</collectingCountry>
, through Scandinavia to 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFC8FFB5BFC30FB48" box="[889,967,1166,1192]" name="Poland" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Poland</collectingCountry>
and the 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFBD5FB5BFB23FB48" box="[1059,1236,1166,1192]" name="Czech Republic" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Czech Republic</collectingCountry>
and throughout the Mediterranean basin east to 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFE37FB67FDE4FB2C" box="[449,531,1202,1228]" name="Greece" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Greece</collectingCountry>
, as well as from 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFD3BFB67FCB2FB2C" box="[717,837,1202,1228]" name="Greenland" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Greenland</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFCB9FB66FC40FB2D" box="[847,951,1203,1229]" name="Morocco" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFC34FB66FC18FB2D" box="[962,1007,1203,1229]" name="Iran" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Iran</collectingCountry>
and the Caucasus. 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFB32FB66FADFFB2C" authorityName="Petagna" authorityYear="1787" box="[1220,1320,1202,1229]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brutia">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFB32FB66FADFFB2C" box="[1220,1320,1202,1229]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">C. brutia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also occurs as a non-native on the west coast of North America, from Oregon north into British Columbia (
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFB46FB03FA9CFB10" author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[1200,1387,1238,1264]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" pagination="364 - 369" refId="ref33036" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2009) Nomenclatural notes on Callitriche (Callitrichaceae) in North America. Novon 19: 364 - 369. https: // doi. org / 10.3417 / 2008030" type="journal article" year="2009">Lansdown 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF89FF9AFF4BFB2FFACAFA28" blockId="8.[136,1452,446,1841]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF4BFB2FFE31FAF4" bold="true" box="[189,454,1274,1300]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Habitats and Ecology:</emphasis>
—In 
<collectingCountry id="A7CD2FE6FF89FF9AFE09FB2FFD91FAF4" box="[511,614,1274,1300]" name="Australia" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Australia</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFD9AFB2EFD27FAF4" authorityName="Petagna" authorityYear="1787" box="[620,720,1274,1301]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brutia">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFD9AFB2EFD27FAF4" box="[620,720,1274,1301]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">C. brutia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is described as growing in water or on mud (
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFB33FB2FFAFBFAF4" authority="Lansdown, 2022" authorityName="Lansdown" authorityYear="2022" box="[1221,1292,1274,1300]" genus="Walsh" pageId="8" pageNumber="283" rank="genus" status="N.G.">Walsh</taxonomicName>
and Entwistle 1999) in drains, creeks and dams (
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFDF0FACBFD72FAD8" author="Bean, A. R." box="[518,645,1310,1336]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" pagination="545 - 554" refId="ref29812" refString="Bean, A. R. (2007) A taxonomic revision of Callitriche L. (Callitrichaceae) in Australia. Austrobaileya 7: 545 - 554." type="journal article" year="2007">Bean 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Herbarium specimen labels indicate that it occurs in water up to 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFA90FACBFA5CFAD9" box="[1382,1451,1310,1337]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="cm" value="50.0">50 cm</quantity>
deep, typically in seasonally inundated areas, in swamps, roadside pools, ponds, lake margins and floodplains, in open woodland, such as 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFEAAFAB3FCA5FA60" authority="Dehnh. (1823: 20)" authorityName="Dehnh." authorityPageNumber="20" authorityYear="1823" box="[348,850,1382,1408]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Eucalyptus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="camaldulensis">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFEAAFAB3FD89FA60" box="[348,638,1382,1408]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Eucalyptus camaldulensis</emphasis>
Dehnh. (1823: 20)
</taxonomicName>
stands or in sedge-lands. In its native range, 
<taxonomicName id="18DA14F5FF89FF9AFAB0FAB2FEEEFA44" authorityName="Petagna" authorityYear="1787" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Callitriche" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="brutia" subSpecies="brutia">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFAB0FAB2FA5CFA60" box="[1350,1451,1382,1409]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">C. brutia</emphasis>
subsp. 
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF23FA5FFEEEFA44" box="[213,281,1418,1444]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">brutia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
typically occurs in ephemeral water bodies and in the draw-down zone of standing waters on the margins of lakes (
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFF18FA7BFE5EFA28" author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[238,425,1454,1480]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" refId="ref33002" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2008) Water starworts of Europe. BSBI Handbook No. 11. Botanical Society of the British Isles, London, UK. 180 pp." type="book" year="2008">Lansdown 2008</bibRefCitation>
). 
<quantity id="1822C293FF89FF9AFE4DFA7BFDE9FA29" box="[443,542,1454,1481]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="9.5" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" unit="m" value="475.0" valueMax="950.0" valueMin="0.0">0–950 m</quantity>
elevation in its native range; no information on elevation in the region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF89FF9AFF4BFA07FD8EF9F1" blockId="8.[136,1452,446,1841]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF4BFA07FEFEFA0C" bold="true" box="[189,265,1490,1516]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Notes:</emphasis>
—Most records on the Australian Virtual Herbarium appear to have been correctly determined and they are mainly accepted here for mapping purposes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF656F76FF89FF9AFF4BF9CFFC61F9D4" blockId="8.[136,1452,446,1841]" box="[189,918,1562,1589]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">
<emphasis id="EDAEB364FF89FF9AFF4BF9CFFE4EF9D4" bold="true" box="[189,441,1562,1588]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251">Conservation Status:</emphasis>
—Least Concern (LC) (
<bibRefCitation id="BB4B1287FF89FF9AFD35F9CFFC7DF9D4" author="Lansdown, R. V." box="[707,906,1562,1588]" pageId="8" pageNumber="251" pagination="164300" refId="ref33126" refString="Lansdown, R. V. (2014 a) Callitriche brutia. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2014: e. T 164300 A 42334457. https: // doi. org / 10.2305 / IUCN. UK. 2014 - 1. RLTS. T 164300 A 42334457. en" type="journal article" year="2014">Lansdown 2014a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
